Now, I've zero interest...

text: I am a MASSIVE fan of the books and have pretty much always had at least one of Philip Reeve's books on the go since I started reading Mortal Engines, so you can be pretty sure that I'll love this film too... However I have to say that the changes that appear to have been made don't seem to be good. Some minor things (no guild marks, potentially no David Shaw, etc.) don't REALLY matter, though could become relevant as the story continues past this point, but the more major things worry me. Overall the aesthetic is fantastic, I can't help feel that London (and indeed the cities in general) look a little small. Scrivener's moon has description of truly vast structures within a small section of the GUT of London (the very bottom tier, where the jaws open into) and that was in an unfinished version of the city, hundreds of years before the events of the original book. It also almost looks too consistent, a key feature of municipal darwinism (the whole philosophy of traction cities) is that, after a successful chase, the predator city will break apart and use its prey to expand itself. There are several small cities that do exactly that in Mortal Engines, indeed Salthook looks very nice in this trailer, but something about London itself just feels off. I could go into detail about most of the rest of the things in here, but that'd be tedious. There is one major, MAJOR problem with this film though and that's Hester Shaw. Her 'scar' here is almost pretty, like it's a fashion accessory. In the books she is actively extremely ugly. 'A terrible scar ran down her face from forehead to jaw, making it look like a portrait that had been furiously crossed out. Her mouth was wrenched sideways in a permanent sneer, her nose was a smashed stump, and her single eye stared at him out of the wreckage.' This is what Hester SHOULD look like. I am immensely worried about the appearances of characters from later in the series if Hester has been made somewhat pretty. Imagine... What if Pennyroyal has some fashion sense, instead of being a more futuristic 6th doctor? What if Smew is a normal height? What if (and this is, potentially, even more important than Hester's appearance) Shrike isn't a towering, terrifying, titan? Despite my concerns, I'm still extremely excited for December... And whatever is released beyond.

text: I was hoping to see the stalker in this trailer there are some things that are already fucked up. Hester Shaw (the woman that tries stabbing the guy in the trailer) is supposed to be ugly. That scare she has is supposed to have taken half her nose and 1 eye. This is important because Thomas (the guy that us chasing Hester) has to kinda get over her hideous appearance. She is also vary rude. Ok i have some spoilers so "SPOILER WARNING!!!" ..............  Valentine (the man Hester tries to kill)  killed Hesters mother and tried to kill her when she was like 8 years old. He failed in killing Hester but succeeded killing her mother and scaring Hester's face. Hester's mother went to the Waste land (North America) and found the construction blue prints and all the necessary information to to build a nuclear Bomb to which they name Medusa. The predator Cities like London prey on smaller cities the people who suppprt these "Mobile Cities" are called "Tractionists" those who oppose are called "Anti-Tractionists" there are some people who still live in Permanente Cities, some who live in Floating Cities and some who live in Flying Cities. The wheeled Predator Cities have soldiers called "Stalkers" stlakers are men who have been killed amd resurrected combimed man and machine, they become cyborgs. They feel no pain and have no emotions. They do not need to eat, drink, sleep or rest. I do believe they have to recharge their power source but they are scary as fuck in the books. In the book Hester almost volunteers to become a Stalker. Thomas stops her. Anyways thats what the movie is based on and a out line of the story and some character motivations. This was you can kinda decide if its the kinda movie you want to spend money on. Oh and the Floating Cities appear in tje sequal "Infernal contraptions"

text: This is endemic in trailers these days. This one gives away every virtually every plot twist that made the book so readable. The McGuffin super weapon was (at least to my ten-year-old self) a surprise, as was Hester's disfiguration and the reveal of Valentine as an antagonist.  Furthermore, Hester in the books was pointedly hideous to look at. She was described as such. She had one eye and no nose, and this was shocking for my ten-year-old self, as it was to the protagonist. It was a subversion of expectation. And Hester's ugliness was part of her character development, having to come to terms with it, yet being a compelling and capable protagonist in spite of it. Jackson has really given this Hester the old Hollywood upgrade. The 'Tyrion treatment', if you will.  Also, weren't Hester and the male (forget his name; Tom?) children, or at most adolescents in the book? Shows like Game of Thrones aged up the protagonists so they could be depicted having sex without breaking any laws, but why do it here? So as to not have this movie come across as 'for kids'? It's a story about massive, mechanised cities that roll around eating each other, but they're trying to Mad Max it.  Can't say I'm impressed so far.

text: The CGI: I want to hope that this is still early days and that the CGI will get better closer to release, like what happened with Jurassic World. That being said, I'm happy with where it's at right now.  The CAST: Love the cast, a bit miffed at the lack of English accents, but hey, it's hollywood. I'm just glad this amazing book is getting a movie!  The SCAR: Not big enough at all - but you know Hollywood. They can't cast a lead actress and not have her pretty! Hopefully, like Thor Ragnarok, they're hiding the actual appearance for the movie so as not to spoil it too much... Things like missing eye/nose. Not likely though...  All in all, this trailer is super exciting, but a little disappointing. I can't wait for the film, but the trailer itself seems to be selling it short. They revealed all the tropes and enough of the story to spoil the underlying thread of the movie, but not enough to really sell it as a worthy watch. I'm glad there's no Shrike,  as I'm excited for the reveal.

text: The only things I find odd, having read the books and being very into the universe, are:  Why does London have the Union Jack plastered on the front? The idea of Britain, or the United Kingdom, vanished long ago. The story is set thousands of years in the future, the world was destroyed in an hour-long war, and cities are basically just tribes... there are no nations anymore.  Secondly, Hester's scar. She's supposed to be blind in one eye, have barely anything left of her nose, and have a hook-shaped, constantly snarling mouth.  Other than that, it's looking great. MEDUSA looks just as I imagined it to be, and all the other things look great too.

text: I'm all for sci-fi, but this doesn't hold a shred of interest for me. The premise is just too preposterous. Some stories should just remain in print and not be adapted to visual media. Also, bandying Peter Jackson's name about any more in no longer a ticket to a quality film. He struck gold with the LOTR films, but his work has been less than stellar since, and the Hobbit trilogy was an abomination full of CGI bloat and mangled story. I don't hold out much hope for this film being interesting, but at least Hugo Weaving will be able to pay the rent.

text: All the people saying "Ew, flop flop flop bla bla bla"... why? This sums up our ridiculous negative hype culture, any book adaptation is "immediately unfaithful", any original material is "generic and thoughtless". Wouldn't it be better if we lived in a world where judgements of the everyday population were made AFTER seeing a film? Being honest, no one cares if people think it will flop, people thought that about Hobbit and that did really well money wise. I personally think that this film looks really good, and Peter Jackson is a perfect person to bring the vision of such large, moving creations to life in the way he did the settings of LotR and Hobbit. Look like it will be quite a spectacle, and I think I will reserve any judgements until AFTERWARDS? Yeah, sounds reasonable doesn't it??

text: That's a big no from me. Directed by the visual-effects artist from King-Kong? No wonder there's a ton of CGI with generic writing and plot. I swear they just took some generic hero story and added CGI mobile attack cities and were like ,"yeah the American people really want to fall asleep to something they've seen 30 different ways before."  From the description: "two opposites, whose paths should never have crossed, forge an unlikely alliance that is destined to change the course of the future." Yeah you'd never cross path with a dude who lives in a city you're being attacked by. I swear they actually wrote a worse love story than Twilight. I feel so bad for the actors, I don't blame them at all.   The only thing that will save this movie is if they just let the bad guy win and the movie ends and there's not a sequel. Just let the bad guy win, he has the power and the super weapon. Don't just plot-armor a love-couple for an entire movie until it ends.

text: If you have not read the books do not look below as massive spoilers to the first book and possibly the movie. Here i'll ramble on a bit on the parts they most likely completely changed. This is following the trailer bit by bit.     EDIT: *HESTER SHAW IS SUPPOSED TO BE HIDEOUS*   "A terrible scar ran down her face from forehead to jaw...Her mouth was wrenched sideways in a permanent sneer, her nose was a smashed stump and her single eye stared at him out of the wreckage..." Credit to the one guy who reminded me of this   FIRST- Hester Shaw never got a hit on Valentine and was interrupted by Tom.                At the end of the chase Hester gives Tom her name before jumping off by herself. There was no clich√© 'hold onto hand tell him this' scene                Valentine is actually human and kind, but has to do things for London that he indeed regrets, he isn't full bad guy unlike how the movie              paints him as he ledges Tom.               At the ledge scene there were supposed to be _many_ witnesses including London guards and an engineer, Pod               Who the hell is that woman Valentine speaks to? (Unless she's the one that sends out Shrike)              The _Jenny Haniver_ ship is meant to be a culmination of tonnes of seperate parts of ships that Anna took as a child, not some amazing              professionally built red ship               1:32-136             They did not meet this way at all...              EGHHH? Anna Fang was not looking for Hester and had no Idea what the Medusa did.               The rest was complete BS as it completely steers off course completely.            Anna Fang was supposed to be dead by then.            Hester could not give a single damn about London.            Tom doesnt want to kill anybody.            AAAAAAAND Shrike as well as Valentine's daughter as well as all Stalkers are taken away completely based off of the trailer.

text: I think %99 of everyone that comments on youtube videos are just chronically negative or needs to be on Effexor.  Gees, I've never even heard of this book, but I am a fan of LOTR.  Guess what....I think this looks pretty cool!    Will it be as good as.... LOTR?   Shawshank Redemption?  Terminator 2?  Aliens?  A Few Good Men?  Jesus of Nazareth?  The Man Who Shot Liberty Valence?  Probably NOT, but guess what....neither is %90 of movies that are made!  You think maybe the bar has been raised just a weeee bit too high?  And just another random comment......Who cares about whether or not a movie is faithful to the book?  Only someone who needs a hobby or a girlfriend.   I watched Jack Nicholson scorch the screen in the Shining before I read the book, and guess what?....the book was a whooooole lot different than the movie.  Did it diminish my love for that movie?..uh, no.     I just think folks get a little too worked up about some things, especially things that are meant to be entertaining.  I sit around with my family, eating chocolate chip cookies and watching movies.  We don't have a notepad, taking notes on plot holes and crap or shredding a movie because it's 'unbelievable'!    Gees, wasn't Star Wars unbelievable back in the day?  Has nobody else thought to themselves one freakun time that Brody could have just injected some potassium cyanide into a big ol bloody piece of Bonita and threw it out there and killed the dadgum shark without having to go through all the Hell they faced in Jaws!!??   My whole point is, isn't there enough problems in the world to worry about than to get all worked up over something meant to get our mind OFF of the world for a while?   Just watch the stinkun movie and get your stinkin panties out of your crack!    It's a freakun MOVIE!!!!!  Enjoy it for what it is!!!!  Just my humble opinion.

text: I've read the books and the moment I flipped the last page of the first one, I began wondering when they'd make a movie out of it. Now we have it and I have no doubt the visuals will be great, but watching the trailers I have my doubts on the 'fun' aspect..  MEDUSA was a twist that was kept from readers until what was the last half, maybe third of the book. The book had its readers waiting for a long time until it revealed what St. Paul had hidden beneath its dome. Then you have this two minute trailer barging in an screaming HEY WE HAVE A LASER WEAPON HERE WITH COOL VISUALS!  I'm sure the trailer could have been done with much more subtlety so that it piques people's interests, but instead it opted to be another one of those half-assed trailers that spilled too much beans for its own good.

text: Yeah the visuals are cool but the characters don't inspire me at all, they all feel pretty bland to me with only some facial scarring on a woman to make her stand out as the main character. Plus the trailer didn't really tell you anything about what the film is about. A girl's mother finds some kind of a book and a gruff man kills her for it, and for some reason 10 years later trouble ensues.  Perhaps there are too many characters in this film, sometimess less is more. E.G. Howls Moving Castle did just fine with Howl, Sophie, a boy, the witch, and a talking fire. And Howl was an interesting character you don't often see, a powerful wizard but a vain pretty-boy who has a meltdown when he dies his hair the wrong colour.   In a western real life film, he would have been yet another musclebound, shaved head, stubbled meathead with a gruff voice and no personality that we have all seen 100 times before.   Plus they all have that slightly panicked, a little sarcastic, really serious voice that every single character in every single modern film has these days. (like Rey in the new Star Wars films, as it adds "drama") - Howl was a more likable, more realistic character than any of them despite being a cartoon boy.

text: I just saw and interview with the main actress talking about her character's disfigurment... just... wow... saying she's disfigured is laughable, and by that I mean saying she's disfigured is funny because disfigurment itself is obviously not funny. She's not disfigured... she has one medium sized scar. There's a difference between having been scarred and having been disfigured. If you wanted to tone down her facial scars that's fine but don't call it disfigurement anymore. Both are traumatizing, and could bring about the same character motivations though obviously you'd have to have the scarring happen more recently than the disfigurement happened in the book, given being disfigured has more stigma around it than having a scar and some disfigured people are outcasts in society. It's like if a soldier came back from war with a scar on his cheek and started telling people "Yeah... I got disfigured in the war.", but that obviously wouldn't happen because the two types of injuries are completely different.

text: I'm looking forward to seeing the film, but I'd be annoyed if I hadn't already read the books at this trailer. Valentine's betrayal alone is a pretty big turning point in the books, even if it happens very early on. They didn't have to show that in the trailer. And lots of people have mentioned it already, but it's still relevant. Hester is supposed to be ugly. Really ugly. That's an important plot point - Tom gradually learns to look beyond pure aesthetics and learns to love the person. Hester is an oddly unique character in YA fiction, because everyone in YA fiction is objectively attractive. A scar does not make you ugly, but the way Hester is described really does (isn't she missing her nose?!). Hollywood just can't resist. It really doesn't think we can root for a character who isn't what most people would consider attractive. It's one of the reasons I love films like Under the Skin - Adam Pearson's character, beyond disfigured, is someone who understands the importance of character over beauty. He's not immediately besotted by someone who looks like Scarlet Johannson (and speaking as a heterosexual male, that's impressive).

text: The most disjointed bag of assorted movies sewn and horrifically welded together ever created.  Want a random collection of characters with no back story?  Come right this way.  Want so many villains that you don't actually know who is wanting what outcome and for what purpose? Beauty this is for you! Alot of movie franchises should start up a class action lawsuit for the amount of straight up stolen ideas copy pasted into this abomination. Visuals?  Yeah gee it looked good,  but went does that even matter when you don't know who is who,  why they know each other,  why villains are acting in such a way and gee how people are even getting around!? Some characters were shown flying, driving and walking, but i'm convinced others had some kind of personal teleportation devices combined with tracking devices.  I am exhausted by how terrible this movie was.

text: Spoiler Alert:   This movie is bad! It felt crammed. Too much was introduced with little to no explanation. It almost felt like Universal told Peter Jackson to squeeze everything from the books into one movie. The last 30 min were a cringe fest and you could see the plot coming a mile away. The lines including "Your history" were so cheesy that it made me want to hurt myself. Also did they do some Star Wars stuff towards the end? The dude flies the plane into the center and blows up the core? Also the bad guy reaches out his hand to the protagonist and basically said "I am your father."? What...  Also cool to have Nick Valentine from Fallout 4 starring a different robot dude we get to know nothing about. This movie basically is a hybrid between Star Wars, Terminator and Wild Wild West.  I walked out about 10 min before the movie ended.   This should have been a Netflix mini series similar to Altered Carbon. That show was brilliant!  p.s. I am not rating the books. just this horrendously paced movie.

text: Just watched it. A typical 21 century blockbuster. Amazing special effects and music. Bland, boring and cliched scenario.   There is an old joke in Russia: "No matter what we try to construct, we always end up building Automat Kalashnikov (AK-47)" Similarly, no matter what Hollywood tries with sci-fi adventure, it always ends up re-making Star Wars.   Here is the template: - Big bad guys (always some sort of dictatorship) trying to conquer the world. - They are building the big gun/ship/DeadStar/etc - Two villains - one is a general manager/manipulator, another is an unstoppable killer - A young hero who fights the bad guys and survives against all odds. - This hero has lost his/her parents during childhood - For additional twist, he/she is also related to main villains (this revealed towards the end, as a big twist).  - A love interest of main hero - Some rogue/pirate who helps the main heroes and rescues them in dire situations  - Some resistance/republic/democracy that fights the bad dictatorship.   Seen this story before ? Yeah, me too. Many times. All the above cliches are in this movie.    The only original element here - Western Europe are bad guys, and Easteners are actually good. Well, that's the biggest and the most original element of this movie.
author: Evgeny Rus

text: SPOILERS SPOILERS   I keep hearing excuses as to why this movie is bombing. Like the time of year it came out, the star power, little known IP etc.  This movie is bad start to finish. The plot is so full of holes it's insane. Everything that happens is predicated on a man...who refuses to acknowledge that  immobile, traditional settlements are  things to respect. In fact he is willing to kill his wife, first daughter, abandon second daughter, so that he can have a weapon? to tear down a wall? So his mobile city can continue ingesting mobile cities? Because......why.? He really is committed..to what? (What?) Who greenlit this script? Quit your job.  Every single character is combination, poorly portrayed, not fleshed out, actual identity unknown, forgotten about at various times. Why should I care about characters the film makers don't respect enough to even construct them to the point that they can be called characters actually.  The being saved, but sold into slavery scene, literally could not have been more predictable.  There is only one small town that gets ingested and it's anticlimactic. The one thing the moviemakers thought would sell this ...thing. They do it once in the first 5 minutes, then hunker down for an hour plus of nonsense.   This is the definition of a horrible movie. It felt like a theme park atrraction. Kind of cool to look at but we know these facades are clearly fake and barely skin deep. All these college kids in their steam punk clothes just waiting for their lunch breaks.   So bad it was sad. Pete Jackson smh. Is this what it's like when Tolkien is not your writer?

text: I‚Äôm a MASSIVE fan of the book series, and when I saw this trailer... My heart, broke? I mean, I LOVE Mortal Engines SO MUCH! However, I feel like the characters that are playing Hester Shaw and Tom Natsworthy in the movie were bad... I‚Äôve seen short clips before I saw the trailer because of estatic I was, but in my opinion, the movie script and acting is just bad... I love the book series so much, and I think it‚Äôs my favourtite series of books, but with what I have just witnessed here, on the trailer, is nothing compared to how I personally enjoyed the books so much. I know, it‚Äôs a book series and the movie is based on the director‚Äôs vision of the story, but I think he could have interpreted the idea better. The director of this movie hasn‚Äôt given the watcher as much of an impact on the story as the actual author, Philip Reeve. So personally, I‚Äôd buy all the books instead of watching the movie, but I haven‚Äôt watched the full movie, just short clips. So, maybe I am just judging it too soon, and I may love it as much as the books, but from just seeing the trailer, I‚Äôm not convinced that the movie is really any good. Now, don‚Äôt get me wrong, I‚Äôm an extremely big fan pf Mortal Engines, and I‚Äôm very passionste about it, but I‚Äôm not convinced the movie is what I‚Äôm looking for. Once again, buy the whole series of books before watching the movie, I mean it.

I have a feeling that they didn't make enough world building, in the books there are several BIG cities, in the movie we only see London, I wanted to explore much much more, darn it. And the crazy editing/clipping gave me a headache, when it was a 1-2 minute dialogue they changed camera like 10 times a second,  why? Otherwise it was amazing but just too little of the good stuff, I wanted to see a lot of different huge moving cities and life aboard, instead of flash-backs and irrelevant dialogue, grrrrr. Nevertheless I really liked it because of the few higlights.

text: Considering all the hate I've been reading, I saw this movie thinking, oh well, it will be pretty bad.  But here's my opinion anyway:  (..Something to keep in mind..) When you see "from the film makers of Lord of the Rings" you should not expect a new Lord of the Rings.  There will never be one again.   BUT ! You can sure expect some next level visuals and audio ! And yes, this movie has some of the best pictures I have ever seen.  That being said, I really enjoyed it. I did not really want it to end, so that's a good movie in my book.  Not every movie has to be a constant goosebump generator. Some people enjoy relaxing action sci-fi movies.

text: This movie was impressive! I have never seen that much cash burned with absolutely no apparent plan or direction. It was basically just WaterWorld on land but not as good. The entire plot and premise of the movie was glossed over in about 10 seconds, maybe Peter Jackson had ambitions of covering that in a Jar-Jar Binks type prequel. I only invoke the star wars reference because he of course decided to throw in a "Luke I am your father" moment that was obvious even from the onset of this dumpster fire. Don't worry though he didn't spend the whole film stealing from Disney's Star Wars, he also dug up a character from one of the Matrix sequels to fly an airship he found on the old set of waterworld. Throw in an anti-hero he took from the Iron Giant and set him on a collision course with rebels inspired by the movie Up. And that's all you really need.

text: I watched Mortal Engines tonight on HBO and it wasn't as bad as people say it was.  It's not perfect and it has its flaws but it also has its good points as well.  The effects are amazing and you can tell they put a lot of effort into making this world.  It's almost as if someone made a movie out of Bioshock. Hugo Weaving is great and the female protagonist is definitely handled a lot better than most of what we get these days.  I think the biggest problem with it is they don't take the time to flesh out this world they've made.  They never really explain what the nature of this world is so you kind of have to guess for yourself as you go along.  It's apparently based on a book series so it's like they made it just for those who have read it rather than the average filmgoer.  I had to look up the article on Wikipedia so I could make sense of it.  All in all, I give it a standard C rating.  It's a good idea and it's entertaining but the execution leaves a lot to be desired.

text: Why did "Mortal Engines" fail at the theater box office?  Many people including me, enjoyed the film.  Here's my answer.  Mortal Engines came out too late just as this type of youth fantasy sci-fi dystopian genre reached overfill and exhaustion with the general public, especially the young audience who had watched, "The Hunger Games", "Divergent", and similar movies.  Had Mortal Engines come out in 2016, it would have met with greater box office success.  I read that Peter Jackson began looking at a film theatrical version of the book series.  But it took too long, nine years to bring the film to fruition.  By then the movie-viewing public had tired of the youth dystopian, sci-fi movie genre.  My opinion is that the earlier had ME appeared, the more money it would have made.  A 2016 or earlier release would have probably added at least another 100 million to the mere 83 million box office receipts, probably even breaking the 200 mark.  In that case, the sequel would have appeared in late 2018 and that is when the series would have run into viewer fatigue with the sci-fi genre.
